Part I - Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

by Joseph Mburu¶

Introduction¶

This report presents data exploration of the Ford GoBike System data. This data was provided by udacity via a link and was used to develop this project. The data was downloaded programatically using python requests library and was then read into pandas dataframe. This dataset conveyed information regarding individual rides that were made in a bike-sharing system. In particular, this data was from the greater San Francisco Bay area. The main aim of this project was to utilize univariate, bivariate, and multivariate visualizations to gain hidden insights into the data.

#drop rows with missing values 
bike.dropna(inplace=True, axis=0)

#convert `bike_id`, `start_station_id`,  `end_station_id` into string data types
bike['start_station_id'] =bike['start_station_id'].astype(str)
bike['end_station_id'] =bike['end_station_id'].astype(str)
bike['bike_id'] =bike['bike_id'].astype(str)
#convert member birth year from float to int
bike['member_birth_year']=bike['member_birth_year'].astype(int)
#convert duration_sec to float
bike['duration_sec']=bike['duration_sec'].astype(float)


#convert start_time and end_time to data time format
bike['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(bike['start_time'])
bike['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(bike['end_time'])

##convert start_time to hours, days, month and year
bike['start_day'] = bike['start_time'].dt.day_name()
bike['start_month'] = bike['start_time'].dt.month_name()
#bike['start_year'] = bike['start_time'].dt.year
##convert end_time to hours, days, month and year

bike['end_day'] = bike['end_time'].dt.day_name()
bike['end_month'] = bike['end_time'].dt.month_name()
#bike['end_year'] = bike['end_time'].dt.year

#calculate the age of the participants when this trip started. 
bike['age']=(2019-bike.member_birth_year)

## convert day, and months into ordered categorical types
ordered_dict ={'start_day':['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday'], 
               'end_day':['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday'], 
                'start_month':['January', 'February', 'March'], 
                'end_month':['January', 'February', 'March']}
for var in ordered_dict:
    ordered_var=pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories =ordered_dict[var])
    bike[var]=bike[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The initial dataset had 183,412 participants and 16 variables. However, after preliminary data wrangling, there was 174,952 participants in the data and 20 variables. Out of the total variables, 6 were numerical variables. In addition, month and day were ordered categories

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I was interested in gaining insights into the months and days of the week when most of the trips were taken and when they ended. I was also interested in knowing the average amount of time take in the trips and whether it was dependent on user_type, member_birth_year, and member_gender

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The following features will be helpful in supporting this investigation

  • duration_sec
  • user_type
  • member_birth_year
  • member_gender
  • bike_share_for_all_trip
  • start_day
  • end_day

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I investigated distributions of individual variables. This aimed to identify unusual points and outliers to allow for additional data cleaning.

I will start by looking at the distribution of duration in sec

In [35]:
#create a function that gives the xlabel, ylabel and title to any graph
def x_y_t(Xlab, Ylab, title):
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(Xlab)
    plt.ylabel(Ylab)

# there's a long tail in the distribution, so let's put it on a log scale instead
bins= 10**np.arange(1, 5+0.1, 0.1)
#set figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
plt.hist(data=bike, x = 'duration_sec', bins=bins)
plt.xscale('log')
x_y_t('duration (sec)',' Count', 'Distribution of Log-transformed trip duration')
plt.xticks([50, 100, 250, 500, 1000, 3000, 6000],[50, 100,250, 500, 1500, 3000, 6000])
plt.show()

Duration in seconds has a long-tailed distribution and was skewed to right. This implies that the highest number of participants took lesser time (seconds) to complete the trip, while few participants took longer time to complete the trip. When plotted on a log-scale, the distribution of the duration of time looks unimodal with peak between 400 and 1000.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The trip duration variable was highly skewed to the right, even after limiting the distribution to 6000 seconds. However, after applying the log-transform, the data looked unimodal, with peak between 400 and 1000. In addition, the age variable was skewed to the right even after limiting the distribution to 80 years. However, on transformation using log10, the data was unimodal with peak between 25 and 45 years.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

When investigating the features, age showed unusual distribution, where some participants were aged above 80 years. It is very unlikely that people aged above 80 years could participate in bike riding trip. As such, any age above 80 years was considered to be an outlier and removed from the analysis.

#A scatter plot of age and duration_sec with log transform on both age and duration
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
bike_sub=bike.sample(1000, replace=False)
def log_trans(x, inverse=False):
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)
sns.regplot(bike_sub['age'].apply(log_trans), bike_sub['duration_sec'].apply(log_trans),  scatter_kws={'alpha':1/5}, x_jitter=0.2)
#add xlabel, ylabel and title
x_y_t('Age', 'Trip duration (sec)', 'Scatter plot of log-age vs. log-duration')
plt.show()

The scatter plot shows that there is a moderate linear relationship between age and trip duration after applying log transformation on the two variables.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Bivariate visualization showed a weak positive linear relationship between age and trip duration. This was as expected because young participants are more likely to ride faster than older participants. The analysis also showed that individuals who were bike customers took slightly more time to complete the trip compared to subscribers. The bivariate visualization also revealed no difference in age between customers and subscribers. This suggests that there was no difference in age distribution between customers and subscribers. We also found that the trib took approximately equal amount of time on average across the six starting days. Moreover, bivariate analysis showed that the number of customers and subscibers was high among males than among females.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Basides the main features of interest, this study examined the association between bike share for all trips and duration in seconds. The results showed that those who shared bike took slightly lesser time than those who did not share the bikes.

We also investigated the relationship between user type, gender and trip duration. Based on the box plot, it was evident that among the participants who were customers, male completed the trip faster than females. Similarly, the box plot shows a slight difference in trip duration between males and females, based on the participants who were subscribers. Thus, regardless of the user type, male participants took lesser time to complete the trip than females.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The multivariate exploration showed a weak linear relationship between age and trip duration for both males and females. we also found a stronger linear relationship between age and trip duration among customers than subscribers. Additionally, the results revealed that conditioned on user type, male participants took lesser time to complete the trip than females.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Suprising interactions was found between age, trip duration and start days. In particular, the relationship between age and trip duration was slightly stronger on Monday and Saturday than on other days.

Conclusions¶

This project explored the Ford Gobike data to gain insights into any interesting associations, and distribution of variables. In particular, exploratory analysis was conducted using univariate, bivariate, and multivariate visualization. Based on the analysis, the following main findings were identified.

  • Trip duration was skewed to the right, but after log-transformation, it was unimodal with peaks between 400 sec and 1000 sec
  • Trips that were started were eventually completed.
  • Most of the trips started on Thursday and Tuesday, while the fewest number of trips were made on saturday.
  • Most of the bike riders, who participated in this trip were aged between 18 and 50 year
  • The number of males who participated in the Ford GoBike trips were more than females.
  • Most of the participants in the Ford GoBike trips were subscribers and not customers.
  • There is a moderate linear relationship between age and trip duration after log transformation of the two variables.
  • Subscribers took lesser time to complete the trip than customers.
  • Male participants appear to complete the trip faster than females.
  • Participants took more time to complete the trip on saturdays than other days of the week.
  • There were more males than females both in the customer and subscriber category.
  • Those who shared bike took slightly lesser time than those who did not share the bikes.
  • Regardless of the user type, male participants took lesser time to complete the trip than females.
